    { type: "paragraph", text: "Section 106 viability review mechanisms have become a standard feature of planning obligations on major residential schemes, particularly in London and high-value areas. For a housing association like Clarion/Latimer operating as both developer and RP, understanding the triggers, methodology, and financial implications of late-stage reviews is essential. These mechanisms are designed to capture increases in scheme value that occur between planning consent and practical completion, redirecting surplus profit towards additional affordable housing — either on-site units or commuted sums." },
    { type: "heading", text: "What Are Late-Stage Viability Reviews?" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "A late-stage review (sometimes called a 'post-implementation' or 'near-completion' review) is a contractual mechanism embedded in a S106 agreement that requires the developer to submit an updated Financial Viability Assessment (FVA) at a defined trigger point — typically when 75–85% of market units have been sold or occupied. The review compares the actual outturn costs and revenues against the assumptions in the original FVA submitted at planning stage. If the scheme has generated surplus profit above an agreed developer return benchmark, a proportion of that surplus is captured as an additional affordable housing contribution." },
    { type: "key_term", term: "Late-Stage Review Mechanism", text: "A clause in a S106 agreement requiring a developer to submit an updated viability appraisal near scheme completion, comparing actual financial performance against the consented viability position, with any surplus above the agreed profit threshold shared with the LPA to deliver additional affordable housing." },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "The rationale is straightforward: if a scheme was consented at, say, 20% affordable housing because the original FVA showed it could not support more, but by completion market values have risen substantially and/or build costs have been contained, it is equitable for the planning gain to be shared. The Greater London Authority's Affordable Housing and Viability SPG (2017, updated) and the London Plan (2021) Policy H5 embed this as standard practice for schemes that do not meet the 35% (or 50% on public land) affordable housing threshold." },
    { type: "heading", text: "The Mechanics: How Clawback Is Calculated" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "The clawback calculation typically follows a defined formula in the S106 agreement. The key inputs are: (1) Actual Gross Development Value (GDV) — based on achieved sales prices and contracted affordable housing revenues; (2) Actual total development costs — including build costs, professional fees, finance, CIL, S106 obligations already met, and marketing; (3) Agreed developer return — usually expressed as a percentage of GDV (typically 15–20% on market housing, 6% on affordable housing); (4) The 'surplus' being the difference between actual profit and the agreed benchmark profit. The surplus is then typically shared 60/40 or 50/50 between the LPA (as additional affordable housing contribution) and the developer, subject to a cap equivalent to policy-compliant affordable housing delivery." },
    { type: "callout", label: "APC Tip — Worked Example", text: "Latimer is delivering a 200-unit mixed-tenure scheme in an outer London borough. The consented scheme provides 25% affordable housing (50 units: 30 Social Rent, 20 Shared Ownership). The original FVA assumed a market GDV of £75m and total costs of £60m, yielding a profit of £15m (20% on GDV). At late-stage review (triggered at 80% market sales), actual market GDV has risen to £82m due to house price growth, while costs came in at £62m. Actual profit is £20m, against a benchmark of £16.4m (20% of £82m). However, the benchmark is recalculated on actual GDV, so the surplus = £20m - £16.4m = £3.6m. Under a 60:40 split in favour of the LPA, £2.16m is payable as a commuted sum or converted to additional on-site affordable units. As the RP partner, Latimer must understand how this affects its business plan — does the clawback reduce the land receipt to the parent group, or does it come off developer profit? This distinction matters for board reporting and Homes England grant compliance." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Implications for Housing Associations as Developer" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "When a housing association like Latimer acts as the developer (rather than purchasing S106 affordable units from a private housebuilder), the late-stage review has distinctive implications. First, the RP's development surplus is treated differently from a private developer's profit margin — Homes England and the Regulator of Social Housing expect surpluses to be recycled into further affordable housing delivery. Second, the 'developer return' benchmark in the S106 may need to reflect the RP's actual cost of capital and required return, which is often lower than the 17–20% a private developer would seek. Negotiating the appropriate profit benchmark at planning stage is therefore critical; if the S106 sets the benchmark at 20% on GDV but the RP is operating at 6–8%, the review mechanism may never trigger, potentially leaving value on the table from the LPA's perspective." },
    { type: "key_term", term: "Deficit/Surplus Sharing Split", text: "The agreed proportion by which any surplus (or in some agreements, deficit) identified at late-stage review is divided between the developer and the LPA. Common splits include 60:40 (LPA:developer) in London, though this is negotiable. The LPA's share is directed towards additional affordable housing." },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "A further complexity arises where Homes England grant has been applied to the affordable units. If a late-stage review results in additional commuted sum payments or additional affordable units, the RP must ensure that the original grant conditions are not breached. For example, if the scheme was appraised on the basis that grant was necessary to make the affordable element viable, but the late-stage review reveals a surplus, Homes England may question whether grant was genuinely needed. This is particularly sensitive under the 2021-26 Affordable Homes Programme (AHP), where grant rates are set per unit and additionality is a key condition." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Negotiating the S106 Review Mechanism at Planning Stage" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "For an Assistant Development Manager at Latimer, the negotiation of the review mechanism clauses at planning stage is as important as the headline affordable housing percentage. Key areas to negotiate include: (a) the trigger point — earlier triggers (e.g., 75% sales) give less certainty on final outturn; later triggers (e.g., 90%) may delay the LPA's receipt; (b) the profit threshold — should it be on GDV or cost, and at what percentage; (c) the cap on additional contributions — typically capped at policy-compliant provision to prevent open-ended liability; (d) the sharing mechanism — percentage split and whether it applies to gross or net surplus; (e) the definition of 'costs' — are abnormals, finance costs, and internal management fees all allowable; (f) dispute resolution — typically referral to an independent surveyor." },
    { type: "callout", label: "APC Tip — Assessor Angle", text: "Assessors will expect you to demonstrate that you understand both the policy rationale and the commercial implications of review mechanisms. Be prepared to explain a specific example where you negotiated or responded to a late-stage review. For instance: 'On our scheme in [borough], I led the preparation of the late-stage FVA submission, working with our cost consultants to verify actual build costs and with the sales team to confirm achieved prices. The review identified a £1.2m surplus, of which £720k was payable to the LPA. I negotiated with the LPA to convert this to two additional shared ownership units on-site rather than a commuted sum, which was more favourable for our business plan because we could apply AHP grant to those units and retain long-term rental income.' This demonstrates Level 3 competence: advising, recommending, and implementing." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Common Pitfalls and Disputes" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "Disputes frequently arise over: (1) the treatment of abnormal costs — developers may seek to include higher-than-anticipated remediation or infrastructure costs to reduce the surplus, while LPAs may challenge whether these were genuinely unforeseen; (2) the valuation of unsold units — if the review triggers before all market units are sold, the FVA must estimate the value of remaining stock, which introduces subjectivity; (3) phased schemes — where development is delivered in phases over many years, the timing and scope of each review phase must be carefully defined to avoid double-counting; (4) the interaction with CIL — some LPAs seek to exclude CIL from allowable costs in the review, arguing it is a separate charge, while developers argue it is a genuine cost of development." },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "For Latimer, phased schemes are particularly relevant. A large estate regeneration programme delivered over 10–15 years may have multiple review points. Each phase's review must be self-contained, using the costs and revenues attributable to that phase, but must also account for shared infrastructure costs that benefit the whole scheme. Getting the S106 drafting right at the outset — with clear cost allocation methodology — is essential to avoid protracted disputes years later." },
    { type: "key_term", term: "Benchmark Land Value (BLV)", text: "The land value adopted in the viability appraisal as the minimum return to the landowner. In late-stage reviews, the BLV is typically fixed at the original consented level and is not revisited, meaning any land value uplift flows into the surplus calculation. For RP-led schemes on their own land, BLV may be set at Existing Use Value plus a premium." },
    { type: "heading", text: "The GLA Approach vs Local Authority Approaches" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "The GLA's approach, set out in the Affordable Housing and Viability SPG and reinforced in the London Plan, is the most codified. It mandates early-stage and late-stage reviews for all schemes that do not meet the Fast Track threshold (35%/50%). The early-stage review triggers if substantial implementation has not commenced within two years of consent. The late-stage review triggers at 75% sales. Outside London, practice varies significantly. Some LPAs have adopted similar SPDs (e.g., Bristol, Manchester), while others have no formal review mechanism policy, relying on ad hoc negotiation. For Latimer schemes outside London, you should check the LPA's local plan and any viability SPD to understand whether review mechanisms are expected." }
